      {
        "id": "fdpyaV1rZ0hPWkW5",
        "title": "Text 6",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p><u><strong>Activity 2: Use the Potentiometer to Control a Mechanical Output</strong></u></p><p>Let’s change our DataFlow program so that it can control a physical servo motor instead of a virtual one.&nbsp;</p>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "A7POy3ESiDQy8zBF",
        "title": "Text 7",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p>You will need the following equipment: </p><p></p>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "3Ll9so1CcIxnrKzS",
        "title": "Equipment Set-up",
        "content": {
          "type": "Image",
          "url": "brain/images/screenshot-2024-06-10-at-8.00.11 am.png",
          "filename": "brain/images/screenshot-2024-06-10-at-8.00.11 am.png"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "NcLH0Soud8vH5LV9",
        "title": "Text 9",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<ol><li>Connect the Arduino board to your computer via the blue USB.&nbsp;</li><li>Click the lighting bolt to pair your Arduino device to your program.</li><li>Select connect device from the drop down menus of both the input and live output blocks.</li><li>&nbsp;On the right side of your Arduino, there are more pins with tiny labels. These pins are capable of outputting a signal to a mechanical device, which is a small servo motor in this case.</li><li>We need to do three things to allow the motor to function.</li></ol><ul><li>Provide a source of power.</li><li>Ground the servo’s own circuit in addition to the potentiometer’s circuit.</li><li>Send a signal out of the arduino and into the servo motor.</li></ul><ol><li>Insert the brown wire into the pin that says GND on the right side of the Arduino to ground it.</li><li>Insert the orange wire into the pin that says 2 on the right side of the Arduino. </li><li>This wire sends the signal to the servo.</li><li>Insert the red wire into the 5V pin on the LEFT side of the Arduino.</li></ol>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "4MANco6SpJKnrxBU",
        "title": "Text 10",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p><em>Are you able to control the motor with the servo? Hooray!</em></p>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "aZpP_Rsf5SJ23Q0R",
        "title": "Text 11",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p><strong>Drag this text tile over to your workspace to answer the questions.</strong></p><ol><li>How does this activity relate to the light bulb demo we used in modules 1 and 2?</li><li>How does a mechanical input at the potentiometer become a mechanical output at the servo? Be as detailed as possible. </li></ol><ul><li>If you need a hint or a model for your response, consider this flow chart.World → Mechanical Input → Electrical Signal → Computer Logic → Electrical Signal → Mechanical Output → World</li></ul>"
          ]
        }
      },
